-- Bunds Fall Amid Optimism Over European Debt Crisis Measures, U.S. Growth
-- B y   L u c y   M e a k i n
-- 2012-01-20T07:52:25Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-20/germany-bunds-decline-amid-optimism-over-debt-crisis-measures-u-s-growth.html
German 10-year bunds fell for a
second day as optimism European officials are moving closer to
resolving the debt crisis and signs the  U.S. economy  is gaining
momentum damped demand for the safest assets.  Two-year German  yields  climbed to the highest level in four
weeks as Greek officials and private creditors prepare to meet
for a third day to seek agreement on a debt swap to reduce the
nation’s debt load. Sales of previously owned U.S. homes rose in
December to the most in more than a year, economists said before
a report today, after data yesterday showed claims for
jobless benefits dropped last week.  Germany ’s 10-year yield rose two basis points, or 0.02
percentage point, to 1.88 percent at 7:48 a.m. London time. The
2 percent bund due in January 2022 fell 0.195, or 1.95 euros per
1,000-euro ($1,298) face amount, to 101.065. The two-year yield
was unchanged at 0.21 percent after climbing to 0.24 percent,
the highest since Dec. 23.  European Union governments set tougher rules on budget
deficits according to the latest draft of a planned fiscal
treaty, bowing to some objections raised by the  European Central
Bank . The blueprint, dated Jan. 19 and obtained by Bloomberg
News, is to be discussed Jan. 23 by EU finance ministers.  Bunds have handed investors a loss of 0.2 percent this
year, according to indexes compiled by Bloomberg and the
European Federation of Financial Analysts Societies. French
bonds have also lost 0.2 percent and Greek debt is down 1.4
percent, the indexes show.  To contact the reporters on this story:
